english:
  title: Epitaph for Master Chun-heon, Honored Senior Counselor Choe Ryang-gyeong of Yuan and Koryo
  author: Lee Je-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Master Chun-heon, the Venerable Choe Ryang-gyeong, whose given name was Mun-do and courtesy name was Hee-min, lived fifty-four years. He passed away on the sixth month, kuija day, in the fifth year of Zhizheng. The auspicious burial date fell on the eighth month, renshi day, and he was laid to rest at the foot of Okgum Mountain, joining his ancestral grave according to proper rites.

    His son, Sa-geom, preceded him in death, leaving only young grandsons. His eldest daughter married Jeong Pho, Left Censor-in-Chief, who remained in the capital and did not return. His second daughter married Min Seon, Inspector of Maps and Registers. At Lady Nah's request, they asked me for these words to inscribe upon stone and place within the tomb. I am old now, and my brush moves reluctantly in such work, yet considering that throughout my life we knew each other as kindred spirits, I could not refuse on principle. I took up my brush and titled it: "Epitaph of Master Chun-heon."

    Some questioned me, saying: "Master Chun-heon rose from the ranks of military officials, and his age is six years below yours—how can you call him 'Master'? There must be some explanation."

    I answered: "Chun-heon is the son of the Lord of Gwangyang, whose name was Seong-ji. His grandfather was the Counselor-Accomplisher and Grand Scholar who retired with honor, named Bi-il. His great-grandfather was the Minister of Households and Scholar of the Hanlin Academy who retired with honor, named U. His maternal grandfather was the Counselor-Accomplisher and Grand Scholar of Studies who retired with honor, Kim Hyun. These were men of virtue and standing in the official class. Yet though the Lord of Gwangyang held the trust of the De Mausoleum, overseeing secrets and selections for more than twenty years, commanding vast influence and renown, Chun-heon served as a guard at the Yuan court, learning the Mongol language and script, dwelling among the silk-robed and jeweled, associating with armored generals—circumstances that might well breed arrogance and indulgence. Yet concerning the investigation of things and the extension of knowledge, the cultivation of self and the ordering of others, he never failed to seek the gate and enter.

    When he ventured forth, bow and sword were in his hands; when he returned within, his eyes fixed upon the written page. The works of Zhu Xi, the two Chengs, and Zhou Dunyi—he gathered and studied them all. Deep into the night he slept, at the cock's crow he rose. He pursued every detail meticulously, probing their profound depths, until what his heart grasped his body performed. Gentle as spring sunshine, clear as autumn waters, even servants and concubines never once witnessed in him a sudden anger or swift joy.

    When the De Mausoleum fled to the western regions, Chun-heon accompanied the Lord of Gwangyang, journeying ten thousand li to Tao and Long to inquire after him. With warm countenance and reverent heart, never faltering but growing ever more devoted, the Lord of Gwangyang found peace as if in his own home.

    When King Chungsuk entered the Shenfu court to pay homage, those in power stirred up fraternal strife, and slanderous voices rose in cacophony—no one escaped untainted. Yet Chun-heon's body remained true to his place, his spirit to righteousness. Upright yet respectful, he and all around him harbored no resentment.

    After mourning his parents for three years, he established a family temple, serving the departed as if they lived. His sons and daughters, all born of his first wife, the Lady Kim, were so well cared for under the Lady Nah that none knew she was their stepmother.

    When he served as Minister of Law and Justice, favorites could not perpetrate their schemes. When sent as emissary to Pyeongyang and Ssangseong, harsh and stubborn men could not deceive him. Upon entering the Secret Council and rising to Counselor, the scholars of the realm rejoiced in his elevation, and the people benefited from his virtue. Yet Heaven granted him no long years, and he passed suddenly away. All mourned as if time itself had betrayed them, some even shedding tears.

    Alas! The Way of Chun-heon was perfected in himself and trusted by others, practiced in his family and extended to his realm. In life, he was the hope of all people; in death, he left them bereft. Search the world today—such a man is utterly rare, scarcely one in an age. How could I, who call myself old, who pride myself on being a scholar, fail to name him Master? How could I?

    Thus the epitaph reads:
    One who bears the scholar's name but not the scholar's way
    Is common as the dust in any age;
    But one who bears not the name, yet is the scholar true—
    In all the world, that is our Master Chun-heon alone.
  footnotes:
    - 'De Mausoleum (德陵): Refers to Emperor Togon-temür of the Yuan dynasty, also known as Emperor Huizong''s posthumous name.'
    - 'The investigation of things and extension of knowledge (格物致知): Core Neo-Confucian concepts emphasizing the cultivation of understanding through careful study of the world.'
    - 'Zhu Xi, the two Chengs, and Zhou Dunyi: The foundational philosophers of Neo-Confucianism—Zhou Dunyi (1017-1073), Cheng Yi and Cheng Hao (the two Chengs), and Zhu Xi (1130-1200).'
    - 'Shenfu court (瀋府): Refers to the Yuan imperial court during a period of political upheaval.'
